Analyzing myriad technologies, from sex robots and military drones to sharing-economy platforms, Atanasoski and Vora show how liberal structures of antiblackness, settler colonialism, and patriarchy are fundamental to human---machine interactions, as well as the very definition of the human. While these new technologies and engineering projects promise a revolutionary new future, they replicate and reinforce racialized and gendered ideas about devalued work, exploitation, dispossession, and capitalist accumulation. Yet, even as engineers design robots to be more perfect versions of the human-more rational killers, more efficient workers, and tireless companions-the potential exists to develop alternative modes of engineering and technological development in ways that refuse the racial and colonial logics that maintain social hierarchies and inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aArtificial intelligencexSocial aspects. 0aAutomationxSocial aspects. 0aRoboticsxHuman factors. 0aRobotsxSocial aspects. 0aTechnological innovationsxSocial aspects. 0aTechnological unemploymentxSocial aspects. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aVora, Kalindi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478004455zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478004455423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478004455.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles